  innerleftmargin=18pt,
  innerrightmargin=18pt,
  innertopmargin=14pt,
  innerbottommargin=14pt
]
\noindent\textbf{Abstract.}\enspace
We apply the Temporal Stability Framework (\tsf{}) dictionary conditions and
transition entropy analysis to 779 Indus Valley inscriptions comprising 7,637 tokens
and 3,726 unique sign types.
Per-sign Shannon entropy $\Hs = -\sum_j p(j \mid s)\log_2 p(j \mid s)$ over
successor distributions reveals a strongly bimodal structure: 72\,\% of
attested signs (2,689 sign types) cluster near zero entropy and function as
\emph{closure signs}; the remaining 28\,\% (1,037 sign types) carry high successor
diversity and function as \emph{option signs}, with the maximum reaching
$H = 5.53$ bits.
The corpus-level Linguistic Structure Score Composite (\LSSC{}) has mean 0.69
and median 0.57.
We compare conditional entropy profiles with \citet{Rao2009}, whose
analysis clustered the Indus script with natural languages rather than
non-linguistic symbol systems.
Our transition entropy framework provides an independent structural test that
does not require decipherment: the bimodal entropy signature is consistent
with a communication system that distinguishes sequence-terminating tokens
from sequence-initiating tokens---a necessary condition of structured language.
The Indus script satisfies the structural conditions of language.
Whether it encodes a specific language remains an open question; this paper
argues that question is separable from the structural one.

\medskip
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Indus Valley script, transition entropy, TSF
dictionary conditions, linguistic structure, undeciphered writing,
Rao et al.\ 2009, LSSC, closure signs, option signs.
\end{mdframed}

