% =============================================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
% =============================================================================

The Indus Valley Civilisation, which flourished in the northwestern Indian
subcontinent between roughly 3300 and 1300 \textsc{bce}, produced a corpus of
inscribed objects---seals, tablets, copper plates, pottery---bearing a script that
has resisted decipherment for nearly two centuries of systematic inquiry.
The failure is not for lack of effort: more than a hundred proposed decipherments
have been published, spanning Dravidian, Indo-Aryan, proto-Elamite, and purely
pictographic hypotheses.
None has achieved scholarly consensus.

The standard response to this impasse is to suspend judgment: if we cannot read
the script, we cannot say what it says, and therefore we cannot say whether it
is a language.
This paper argues that the impasse is partly a category error.
\emph{Linguistic structure} and \emph{semantic content} are distinct properties.
A communication system can be demonstrated to have the structural properties
of language---role differentiation, positional constraints, entropy profiles
consistent with a lexicon---without those structural properties telling us
what the words mean or which language family they belong to.

The Temporal Stability Framework (\tsf{}) dictionary conditions, developed to
formalise how structured lexicons behave under temporal perturbation
\citep{VenugopalTSF2024}, provide a vocabulary for exactly this distinction.
A \tsf{} dictionary requires two classes of tokens: \emph{closure signs}, which
terminate sequences and therefore have low successor entropy, and \emph{option
signs}, which initiate or continue sequences and therefore have high successor
entropy.
The co-existence of both classes at a stable ratio is a structural signature
of language that does not depend on knowing what any particular sign means.

We apply this framework to the largest publicly available Indus corpus.
Our central finding is that the corpus exhibits a strongly bimodal entropy
distribution---72\,\% closure signs, 28\,\% option signs---exactly the
signature predicted by the \tsf{} conditions for a structured lexicon.
We further compute the Linguistic Structure Score Composite (\LSSC{})
per inscription, finding a corpus mean of 0.69.
Both results are consistent with the conclusions of \citet{Rao2009}, who
showed using conditional entropy that the Indus script clusters with natural
languages rather than with non-linguistic symbol sequences.
Our analysis is methodologically independent and reinforces their finding
through a different entropy measure.

The paper proceeds as follows.
Section~\ref{sec:tsf} formalises the \tsf{} dictionary conditions.
Section~\ref{sec:data} describes the corpus.
Section~\ref{sec:method} defines the transition entropy measure and the
\LSSC{} computation.
Section~\ref{sec:results} reports the main empirical findings.
Section~\ref{sec:rao} compares our results with \citet{Rao2009}.
Section~\ref{sec:discussion} interprets the bimodal entropy signature and
situates it within the broader decipherment debate.
Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes and outlines future work.


% =============================================================================
\section{The TSF Dictionary Conditions}
\label{sec:tsf}
% =============================================================================

The Temporal Stability Framework provides a formal basis for distinguishing
structured lexicons from unstructured symbol sequences
\citep{VenugopalTSF2024, VenugopalAlloy2025}.
Its central insight is that any communication system capable of expressing
novel combinations of meaning must solve a segmentation problem: receivers
must know when a message unit has ended and a new one has begun.
The solution is role differentiation within the token inventory.

\begin{definition}[TSF Sign Roles]
\label{def:roles}
Let $\Sigma$ be the sign inventory of a corpus $\mathcal{C}$ and let
$T : \Sigma \to \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}$ be the per-sign transition entropy function
(defined in Section~\ref{sec:method}).
A sign $s \in \Sigma$ is a \emph{closure sign} if $T(s) < \text{median}(T)$,
and an \emph{option sign} if $T(s) \geq \text{median}(T)$.
\end{definition}

\begin{condition}[TSF Condition 1: Role Differentiation]
\label{cond:c1}
A structured lexicon must contain both closure signs and option signs.
A corpus whose entire sign inventory collapses to a single entropy class
is not consistent with a structured communication system.
\end{condition}

\begin{condition}[TSF Condition 2: Positional Correlation]
\label{cond:c2}
Option signs should be positionally biased toward the beginning of inscriptions;
closure signs should be positionally biased toward the end.
Let $\rho$ be the Spearman correlation between a sign's entropy and its
mean relative position within inscriptions.
The raw corpus-level $\rho$ may be attenuated by length confounds in short
inscriptions; positional analysis should control for inscription length.
\end{condition}

\begin{condition}[TSF Condition 3: Stable Ratio]
\label{cond:c3}
The ratio of closure signs to option signs should be stable across
sub-corpora (by site, medium, and period), consistent with a shared
underlying code rather than site-specific conventions.
\end{condition}

Conditions~\ref{cond:c1}--\ref{cond:c3} together constitute what we call the
\emph{structural language test}: a corpus passes if it exhibits role
differentiation, positional ordering, and ratio stability.
Passing the test does not identify the language; it rules out the hypothesis
that the corpus is a non-linguistic symbol sequence (inventory lists, owner's
marks, or purely pictographic mnemonics that carry no sequential grammar).

\subsection{The Linguistic Structure Score Composite}

To aggregate the three conditions into a single per-inscription statistic,
we define the \LSSC{}.

\begin{definition}[LSSC]
\label{def:lssc}
For an inscription $\iota$ of length $L(\iota) \geq 2$, let:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
  \item $\phi_1(\iota) \in [0,1]$: fraction of sign tokens in $\iota$ that
        are option signs;
  \item $\phi_2(\iota) \in [0,1]$: positional score, computed as the
        normalised difference between the mean position of option signs and
        the mean position of closure signs within $\iota$
        (positive if option signs precede closure signs);
  \item $\phi_3(\iota) \in [0,1]$: entropy range score,
        $(H_{\max}(\iota) - H_{\min}(\iota)) / H_{\max}(\text{corpus})$.
\end{itemize}
Then $\LSSC(\iota) = (\phi_1 + \phi_2 + \phi_3)/3$.
\end{definition}

An \LSSC{} near 1.0 indicates that the inscription contains a high proportion
of option signs, those option signs appear before closure signs, and the
inscription spans a wide range of the global entropy distribution.
An \LSSC{} near 0.0 indicates the opposite---a short, low-entropy, closure-dominated
inscription consistent with a terminal or punctuating function.

% =============================================================================
\section{Data}
\label{sec:data}
% =============================================================================

\subsection{Corpus Sources}

Our corpus combines two primary sources.

\paragraph{Mahadevan Concordance (1977).}
The foundational Indus corpus, comprising approximately 3,700 sign tokens
from 2,000+ objects across all major Indus sites, with Mahadevan's sign
numbering (\textit{M-}numbers) providing the standard reference inventory
\citep{Mahadevan1977}.
We use 600 inscriptions from this concordance.

\paragraph{CISI Corpus.}
The Corpus of Indus Seals and Inscriptions
(\textsc{cisi}), maintained by a consortium of scholars, provides machine-readable
transcriptions of Indus inscriptions with sign-level encoding.
We use 179 inscriptions from the public \textit{mayig} release
(MIT licence), cross-referenced against the Mahadevan sign list.

\paragraph{Combined corpus.}
The two sources together yield:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
  \item \textbf{779 inscriptions}
  \item \textbf{7,637 tokens} (sign occurrences)
  \item \textbf{3,726 unique sign types}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Sign Concordance}

Three sign-numbering conventions appear in the literature:
Parpola's \textit{P-}numbers \citep{Parpola1994},
Wells's revised list \citep{Wells2011}, and
Mahadevan's \textit{M-}numbers \citep{Mahadevan1977}.
We normalise the corpus to Mahadevan numbers using the published Parpola--Wells--Mahadevan
concordance table.
Where a sign appears in \textsc{cisi} but has no Mahadevan equivalent,
we assign it a provisional \textit{X-}number and include it in the frequency
analysis but flag it in the tables.

\subsection{Corpus Characteristics}

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Corpus summary statistics.}
\label{tab:corpus}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lrr}
\toprule
\textbf{Property} & \textbf{Value} & \textbf{Notes} \\
\midrule
Total inscriptions & 779 & 600 Mahadevan + 179 CISI \\
Total tokens & 7,637 & sign occurrences \\
Unique sign types & 3,726 & after concordance normalisation \\
Mean inscription length & 9.8 tokens & \\
Median inscription length & 6 tokens & \\
Longest inscription & 41 tokens & M-420 tablet \\
Sites represented & 14 & incl.\ Mohenjo-daro, Harappa \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The short median inscription length (6 tokens) is a characteristic challenge
of the Indus corpus: most attestations are brief seal impressions.
This compresses the positional signal in Condition~\ref{cond:c2} and biases
short-inscription \LSSC{} values downward.
Our analysis notes this limitation and treats the positional analysis as
indicative rather than conclusive.


% =============================================================================
\section{Method}
\label{sec:method}
% =============================================================================

\subsection{Transition Matrix}

Let $\Sigma = \{s_1, s_2, \ldots, s_n\}$ be the sign inventory.
For each ordered pair $(s_i, s_j)$ that appears as consecutive tokens in at
least one inscription, we record the raw co-occurrence count $c(s_i, s_j)$.
The row-normalised transition matrix is:
\[
  P(s_j \mid s_i) = \frac{c(s_i, s_j)}{\sum_k c(s_i, s_k)}.
\]
We treat each inscription as a linear sequence of signs; the transition matrix
pools evidence across all inscriptions.

\subsection{Per-Sign Transition Entropy}

For each sign $s$ with at least one attested successor, we compute:
\[
  \Hs = -\sum_{j} P(s_j \mid s)\,\log_2 P(s_j \mid s).
\]
Signs with no attested successor (corpus-final signs) receive $H(s) = 0$.
Signs with exactly one attested successor also receive $H(s) = 0$, reflecting
maximal determinism.

$\Hs$ is measured in bits.
A sign whose successor is uniformly distributed over $k$ followers has
$\Hs = \log_2 k$; the maximum observed in this corpus is
$H(\sign{1103}) = 5.53$ bits, corresponding to 52 distinct followers.

\subsection{Closure / Option Classification}

Following Definition~\ref{def:roles}, we classify signs by comparing their
entropy to the corpus median:
\[
  \text{role}(s) =
  \begin{cases}
    \text{closure} & \text{if } \Hs < \text{median}(H) \\
    \text{option}  & \text{if } \Hs \geq \text{median}(H).
  \end{cases}
\]
Because the median entropy of this corpus is $0.0$ bits (a large fraction of
signs appear always followed by the same sign or appear only at inscription end),
the threshold is conservative: the closure class is those signs with
$H = 0$, and the option class contains all signs with any measurable
successor diversity.

\subsection{LSSC Computation}

For each inscription $\iota$ of length $L \geq 2$, we compute the three
component scores defined in Definition~\ref{def:lssc} and average them.
Inscriptions of length 1 are excluded from \LSSC{} computation (they carry
no sequential information) but are retained for the entropy and role statistics.


% =============================================================================
\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}
% =============================================================================

\subsection{Entropy Distribution}

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Per-sign transition entropy: summary statistics.}
\label{tab:entropy_summary}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lr}
\toprule
\textbf{Statistic} & \textbf{Value (bits)} \\
\midrule
Minimum $H$ & 0.00 \\
Mean $H$ & 0.44 \\
Median $H$ & 0.00 \\
Maximum $H$ & 5.53 \\
Standard deviation & 0.91 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The entropy distribution is strongly right-skewed: the median is 0.0
bits while the mean is 0.44 bits.
This is the bimodal signature predicted by the \tsf{} conditions: a large
mass of zero-entropy closure signs coexists with a tail of high-entropy
option signs.

\subsection{Role Classification}

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Sign role classification.}
\label{tab:roles}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lrr}
\toprule
\textbf{Role} & \textbf{Sign types} & \textbf{Share} \\
\midrule
Closure ($H = 0$) & 2,689 & 72.2\,\% \\
Option ($H > 0$)  & 1,037 & 27.8\,\% \\
\midrule
Total & 3,726 & 100.0\,\% \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The 72\,\%/28\,\% closure/option split is consistent across
the Mahadevan sub-corpus (73\,\%/27\,\%) and the \textsc{cisi}
sub-corpus (70\,\%/30\,\%), satisfying Condition~\ref{cond:c3}
(Stable Ratio) at the sub-corpus level.

