\end{table}

\subsection{Top Closure Signs}

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{Top 10 closure signs by frequency (all with $H = 0$).}
\label{tab:top_closure}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lrrl}
\toprule
\textbf{Sign (M-\#)} & \textbf{Occurrences} & \textbf{Unique follower} & \textbf{Notes} \\
\midrule
\rowcolor{shaderow} 59 & 312 & 1 & Canonical terminal; ``fish'' sign \\
100 & 289 & 1 & \\
\rowcolor{shaderow} 211 & 241 & 1 & \\
305 & 198 & 1 & \\
\rowcolor{shaderow} 140 & 176 & 1 & \\
79 & 154 & 1 & \\
\rowcolor{shaderow} 47 & 131 & 1 & Jar sign; frequent seal terminal \\
183 & 119 & 1 & \\
\rowcolor{shaderow} 22 & 108 & 0 & Corpus-final only \\
361 & 97 & 0 & Corpus-final only \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The canonical ``fish'' sign (M-59) is the most frequent closure sign,
appearing 312 times with exactly one attested successor, consistent with
its known role as a near-obligatory element of Indus seal inscriptions.

\subsection{LSSC Distribution}

\begin{table}[htbp]
\centering
\caption{LSSC summary statistics (779 inscriptions, length $\geq 2$).}
\label{tab:lssc}
\small
\begin{tabular}{lr}
\toprule
\textbf{Statistic} & \textbf{Value} \\
\midrule
Mean \LSSC{} & 0.69 \\
Median \LSSC{} & 0.57 \\
Standard deviation & 0.21 \\
10th percentile & 0.41 \\
90th percentile & 0.94 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The mean \LSSC{} of 0.69 is substantially above 0.5, the threshold that
corresponds to an inscription with a balanced option/closure profile and
correct positional ordering.
This corpus-wide elevation is consistent with the hypothesis that the
inscriptions encode structured sequences rather than random symbol
combinations.

\subsection{TSF Condition 2: Positional Correlation}

The raw Spearman correlation between per-sign entropy and mean relative
position is $\rho = +0.51$ ($p < 0.001$).
The positive sign is in the predicted direction: higher-entropy (option)
signs tend to appear earlier in inscriptions, lower-entropy (closure) signs
tend to appear later.

However, this raw $\rho$ conflates two effects: genuine positional ordering
and a length confound, because short inscriptions are more likely to consist
entirely of closure signs.
A partial-correlation analysis controlling for inscription length reduces
the estimate; we treat $\rho = +0.51$ as an upper bound on the positional
signal, with the true partial correlation requiring further positional
modelling.

\begin{remark}[Length Confound]
\label{rem:length}
The median inscription length of 6 tokens means that approximately half
of all inscriptions are too short for positional analysis to be reliable.
Future work should stratify by inscription length and analyse only
inscriptions of length $\geq 8$ tokens, which constitute roughly
35\,\% of the corpus.
\end{remark}


% =============================================================================
\section{Comparison with Rao et al.\ (2009)}
\label{sec:rao}
% =============================================================================

\citet{Rao2009} applied conditional entropy to the Indus corpus and
compared it with a diverse set of natural languages (Sanskrit, Old Tamil,
Sumerian, English) and non-linguistic symbol sequences (Fortran code,
DNA, human brain signals).
Their central finding: the Indus script's conditional entropy profile is
statistically indistinguishable from natural language and statistically
distinguishable from the non-linguistic comparators.

Our analysis is methodologically independent in three respects:
\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
  \item We use \emph{transition entropy} (per-sign successor distribution)
        rather than \emph{conditional entropy} (bigram entropy averaged
        across the corpus).
  \item We introduce the closure/option role classification, which provides
        a discrete interpretation of the continuous entropy spectrum.
  \item We introduce the \LSSC{} as a per-inscription aggregate, enabling
        inscription-level rather than only corpus-level inference.
\end{enumerate}

Despite these differences, our findings are consistent with \citet{Rao2009}.
The bimodal entropy distribution we document is the transition-entropy
analogue of the conditional entropy clustering they report.
The 72\,\%/28\,\% closure/option split is the structural signature that
produces the conditional entropy profile they measure.

\begin{proposition}[Consistency with Rao et al.]
\label{prop:rao}
Let $H_c$ denote the conditional entropy of the Indus corpus as measured by
\citet{Rao2009}, and let $H_t$ denote the transition entropy distribution
measured in this paper.
Both $H_c$ and the bimodal structure of $H_t$ are consistent with the
hypothesis that the Indus script is a natural language; both are inconsistent
with the hypothesis that it is a non-linguistic symbol sequence.
The two analyses use different entropy measures and different corpora;
their agreement strengthens the inference.
\end{proposition}


% =============================================================================
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
% =============================================================================

\subsection{The Bimodal Entropy Signature as a Language Test}

The striking feature of the Indus entropy distribution is not the mean
(0.44 bits) or the maximum (5.53 bits) in isolation, but the bimodal shape:
a large zero-entropy mass and a continuous tail.
This shape is precisely what the \tsf{} dictionary conditions predict for
a structured communication system.

A non-linguistic system---a set of owner's marks, a pictographic inventory,
or a tally system---would produce a different distribution.
Owner's marks would cluster near zero for all signs (each object has a
unique mark; marks do not precede each other).
Pictographic inventories would show moderate entropy uniformly across signs
(each picture has a small number of conventional successor pictures).
A tally system would show near-zero entropy everywhere (tallies are
repeated identical signs).

The Indus distribution matches none of these alternatives.
It matches the distribution expected of a lexicon with role-differentiated
tokens.

\subsection{The Dravidian Hypothesis}

The bimodal entropy signature does not resolve the question of whether the
Indus script encodes a Dravidian language, an ancestral Indo-Aryan variety,
a language isolate, or something else entirely.
What it does is constrain the space of plausible hypotheses: the script
is structured, sequential, and role-differentiated.
Any proposed decipherment must account for this structure.

The Dravidian hypothesis \citep{Parpola1994} is consistent with the
structural evidence but not entailed by it.
Tamil and other Dravidian languages have their own transition entropy
profiles; comparing those profiles with the Indus profile is the natural
next step.
If the Indus closure/option ratio and entropy distribution match
Old Tamil (as attested in the Tolkappiyam and Sangam corpus) more closely
than they match Sanskrit or Sumerian, that would provide indirect structural
evidence for the Dravidian hypothesis.
We leave this comparison to future work.

\subsection{What This Analysis Does Not Prove}

We have shown that the Indus script satisfies the structural conditions
of language.
We have not shown:
\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
  \item That the script encodes any particular language;
  \item That the sign values can be recovered without a bilingual text;
  \item That the signs correspond to syllables, morphemes, logograms,
        or some combination;
  \item That the corpus is internally homogeneous (different sites, periods,
        and media may encode different systems).
\end{enumerate}

These remain open questions.
The value of the structural test is precisely that it does not pretend to
answer them: it establishes a necessary condition (structured language) while
remaining silent on sufficient conditions (specific decipherment).


% =============================================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
% =============================================================================

We have applied transition entropy analysis and the \tsf{} dictionary
conditions to 779 Indus Valley inscriptions comprising 7,637 tokens.
The main findings are:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Bimodal entropy distribution.}
        72\,\% of attested signs (2,689 sign types) have zero transition
        entropy and function as closure signs; 28\,\% (1,037 sign types)
        have positive entropy and function as option signs.
        This bimodal structure is the transition-entropy signature of a
        structured lexicon and is inconsistent with non-linguistic symbol
        sequences.

  \item \textbf{LSSC.}
        The Linguistic Structure Score Composite has a corpus mean of 0.69
        and a median of 0.57, both above the 0.5 neutral threshold,
        indicating that most inscriptions exhibit the structural properties
        predicted for structured language.

  \item \textbf{Positional ordering.}
        The raw Spearman correlation between sign entropy and mean
        inscription position is $\rho = +0.51$, in the direction predicted
        by the \tsf{} Condition~2 (option signs before closure signs).
        This result requires positional modelling to correct for the length
        confound.

  \item \textbf{Consistency with Rao et al.\ (2009).}
        Our independent analysis using transition entropy rather than
        conditional entropy converges on the same conclusion: the Indus
        script has the entropy profile of natural language.
\end{enumerate}

The structural language test provided by the \tsf{} conditions is
falsifiable: a corpus that does not exhibit role differentiation, positional
ordering, or ratio stability would fail it.
The Indus script passes.

\subsection*{Future Work}

The highest-priority extension is a Tamil entropy comparison.
The Tolkappiyam (circa 3rd century \textsc{bce}--5th century \textsc{ce})
and the Sangam corpus available at \href{https://www.tamilvu.org}{tamilvu.org}
provide a machine-readable Old Tamil corpus.
Computing transition entropy over that corpus and comparing the closure/option
ratio and \LSSC{} distribution with the Indus results would provide the
first direct structural comparison between the Indus script and a candidate
language family.

A second extension is site-stratified analysis: Mohenjo-daro, Harappa,
Lothal, and Dholavira may differ in their sign inventories and entropy
profiles in ways that carry information about regional variation or script
evolution.

A third extension is inscription-length stratification, which would resolve
the positional length confound identified in Remark~\ref{rem:length} and
provide a cleaner test of Condition~\ref{cond:c2}.

